IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: INCIDENT CAPTURED BY BWC AND MVR 23-MSP-017751 DUI#: 23-079 ATTACHMENTS: Copy of DR-15 Copy of MSP Form 34 Copy of License Return Copy of Registration Return Copy of Search Warrant Copy of Information Exchange ACCUSED: Maura Ashlynn Onkst 3135 Westminster St Manchester, MD 21102 W/F DOB: 5/10/2000 443- NARRATIVE: On 5/19/2022, I was on duty in full uniform operating marked MSP Vehicle G-19. On 5/19/2023 at approximately 0020 hours, I was on the scene of a motor vehicle collision at the intersection of Littlestown Pike and Bachmans Valley Road. Because of this collision, all traffic in the area was stopped and the road was closed in all directions. At approximately 0021 hours, I was approached by a Hispanic male and advised that there was a lady on the ground among the vehicles that had been stopped. I then responded to the area where the male was motioning towards and discovered that there was a secondary collision on Littlestown Pike north of Bachmans Valley Road. Upon my arrival, I observed a female subject possitio0ned on her hands and knees in the southbound lane of Littlestown Pike. I further observed that there was a black passenger car with heavy front end damage, a horse drawn buggy with complete, and a blue pickup with rear end damage all in the southbound lane and shoulder area. I contacted the MSP Westminster Barrack and advised them of the situation. I also observed a young boy laying face up on the ground directly adjacent to the horse drawn buggy. The boy was unconscious and breathing sporadically. I immediately requested aviation and reconstruction responses. Over the course of my investigation, I determined that there was a fourth vehicle that was involved and that it was on the shoulder area in front of the blue pickup. I then identified the at fault vehicle as a black Kia Forte bearing MD Registration 8FG4373. PHASE 1 VEHICLE IN MOTION: I did not observe the vehicle in motion. PHASE 2 PERSONAL CONTACT: I made contact with the operator of the Black Kia Forte, later identified her as Maura Ashlynn Onkst (W/F DOB: 5/10/2000) by her MD Identification Card. Onkst advised that she was traveling southbound on Littlestown Pike and she did not see that traffic was stopped for the previous collision. Onkst stated that once she saw the traffic, she tried to stop as fast as I could and I just smashed into the back of everybody. Onkst advised that she was traveling at approximately 55 mph. Onkst denied having sustained any injuries during the collision. Onkst stated that she was coming from the Maryland Mallet where she only had one drink, I swear to God. I then requested Onksts license insurance and registration. Onkst stated that the requested documents were inside of her vehicle. I then looked through the windows of the vehicle. It was at that time that I observed an open Angry Orchard Crisp Apple Cider can in the child safety seat located in the rear passenger side seat. I opened the door and retrieved the can and observed it to be slightly cool to the touch consistent with the ambient temperature of the evening. I observed that there was approximately 1/8 of the beverage still remaining in the can. I then observed the vehicles driver side door to be ajar an open liquor bottle in the door compartment in plain view. I did not note what liquor type it was at that time. I further observed that it was partially empty. I then requested Onksts information again. Onkst stated that she has a MD Learners Permit but had lost it previously. While speaking with Onkst, I detected a moderate odor of alcohol emanating from her breath and person, Onkst then provided me with a MD Identification Card. Onkst then retrieved a folder from the passenger side floorboard. Onkst opened the folder then began to stare at the contents and not retrieve any documents. I was then able to retrieve the registration card for the vehicle. Onkst was not able to provide proof of valid insurance at that time. I then instructed Onkst to speak with paramedics as I continued my investigation of the collision. Due to my observations thus far including: the severity of the collision, Onksts admission to consuming alcohol prior to operating a motor vehicle, the moderate odor of alcohol emanating from Onksts breath and person, Onksts glassy eyes, Onksts statement that she did not see stopped vehicles in the lane of travel, and the open and partially consumed containers of alcohol inside of the vehicle I suspected that Onkst was intoxicated and impaired by the presence of alcohol in her blood. PHASE 3- PRE ARREST SCREENING: I am certified by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) to administer standardized field sobriety tests (SFSTs). SFSTs were conducted on the shoulder of southbound Littlestown Pike prior to Bachmans Valley Road. The testing area was level, was hard, and was free of any debris that would inhibit testing. Onkst was not wearing glasses, and she denied wearing contacts. Onkst advised that she is farsighted. Onkst denied having and disabilities or physical ailments that would inhibit testing. Onkst denied being prescribed any medications. Onkst stated that when she spins around a lot, she gets dizzy. Onkst advised that she felt fine and was not suffering from any injuries. Onkst stated that she only had one beer and that it was a tall Angry Orchard draft. Onkst advised that she stopped consuming alcohol at approximately 2330 hours in order to be sober enough to operate a motor vehicle. Onkst stated that she arrived at the Maryland Mallet and began consuming alcohol at approximately 2130-2200 hours. Onkst then changed her statement and advised that she consumed two beers at the Maryland Mallet. I then attempted to confirm that Onkst had not consumed any alcohol after she left the Maryland Mallet and she then advised that she had two beers and one shot to drink that night. Onkst stated that they left the Maryland Mallet at approximately 2400 hours, and that she did not have any additional alcohol after leaving. HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (6/6): The first test that was conducted was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (HGN) test. I used a pen as the stimulus. The stimulus was passed horizontally at a distance of 12-15 inches and slightly above eye level in front of Onksts eyes. I instructed her to follow the stimulus with her eyes only. Onkst stated that she understood the instructions to keep her head still. This test was conducted with Onkst facing northbound away from all flashing emergency lights. Onksts pupils were equal in size and both eyes tracked equally prior to the test. Onkst displayed a lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes, distinct and sustained nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes, and onset of nystagmus prior to forty-five (45) degrees in both eyes. Onkst had to be reminded twice to keep her head still and once to follow the stimulus with her eyes. Onkst displayed six of six validated clues of HGN (6/6). I did observe the presence of vertical nystagmus. WALK AND TURN (7/8): I explained and demonstrated the instructional phase in which Onkst was instructed to put her right foot in front of her left foot in a heel to toe manner and to keep both arms at her side and to remain in that position until told otherwise. Once Onkst assumed the instructional position, I explained and demonstrated the walking phase in which Onkst was instructed to take nine steps in a heel to toe manner while counting out loud, keeping her arms down at her sides, while looking down at her feet the entire time. Upon her ninth step, Onkst was instructed to turn while keeping her lead foot planted by taking a series of small steps around her lead foot, and to take nine heel to toe steps in the same manner back in the opposite direction. Onkst was instructed to not stop completing the test until she had completed it in its entirety. While assuming the instructional position, Onkst began to complete the test prior to being told to do so. Onkst was unable to remain in the instructional position without attempting to complete the test during the explanation of the test. I then instructed Onkst to assume the position she stood in for the HGT test with her heels and toes together. Prior to asking Onkst to complete the test, she was instructed to and assumed the instructional position. Once in the instructional position again, Onkst was instructed to complete the test. Onkst missed heel to toe on steps two three four five six seven eight on the first set of steps. Onkst stepped off line on steps five six eight on the first set of steps. Onkst stopped walking after completing the first set of steps. Onkst took a total of twenty-one steps on the first set of steps. Onkst advised that that was the requested nine steps. Onkst then completed the turn unsatisfactorily by pivoting and moving both feet to turn around. Onkst missed heel to toe on all nine steps of the second set of steps. Onkst stepped off line on steps two four and five of the second set of steps. Onkst took a total of ten steps on the second set of steps. Onkst displayed seven of the eight validated clues for the Walk and Turn Test (7/8). ONE LEG STAND (3/4): The test was explained and demonstrated prior to Onkst attempting the test. Onkst was instructed to lift either foot approximately six inches off of the ground while keeping the base of her foot parallel to the ground, keeping her arms down at her sides, while counting out loud by thousands until told to stop. Onkst began the test by lifting her left foot. Onkst put her foot down on the eighth second of the test, the tenth second of the test, and the fifteenth second of the test. Onkst used her arms for balance from the twelfth second of the test until the twentieth second of the test. Onkst swayed during the twelfth second of the test. Onkst displayed three of four validated clues of the One Leg Stand test (3/4), and in thirty seconds Onkst only counted to nineteen. Onkst was offered a preliminary breath test (Alco Sensor III SN: 00014040). The preliminary breath test indicated a result of 0.20 grams of alcohol. Note: the Alco Sensors calibration was tested after the stop and found to be within acceptable limits. Based on my training knowledge and experience in the field of DUI/DWI enforcement and the evidence gathered thus far, I determined that Onkst was intoxicated and impaired by the presence of alcohol in her blood. Due to my observations, I placed Onkst under arrest for driving under the influence of alcohol at 2039 hours. Onkst was then transported to the MSP Westminster Barrack. I confirmed that Onkst was able to read and write English. I read Onkst a DR-15 Advice of Rights. Onkst advised that she would not agree to submit to the breath alcohol concentration test at 0208 hours. Onkst stated she would rather submit to a blood draw. Based on my observations thus far, I completed a Search Warrant to obtain a blood sample from Onkst. Judge Danz of the Carrol County District Court signed the Search Warrant on 5/19/23 at 0251 hours. I then transported Onkst to Carroll Hospital with Blood Kit #G-450 and the Search Warrant to obtain a blood sample. RN Anna Miller collected the blood sample at 0257 hours. A copy of the Search Warrant and Dr-15 were left with Onkst. Onkst was then released to the care of CHC. The blood kit was then processed and the MSP Westminster Barrack in accordance with MSP Policy and Procedure. I request this case remain open pending further investigation. All events occurred in Carroll County. CASE OPEN

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Summary of Investigation On Friday, May 19, 2023, at approximately 0025 hours, the State of Maryland Department of State Police Westminster Barrack in the county of Carroll responded to the area of Maryland Route 97 and Maryland Route 496 for a vehicle collision. Upon arrival of Troopers to the scene, a four (4)-vehicle collision was discovered. Troopers identified the following: Vehicle 1 2018 Kia Forte Operator Maura Ashlynn Onkst, May 10, 2000 Passenger Kourtney Alexandra Black, August 17, 2000 Vehicle 2 Horse and Buggy Operator John Fisher, November 14, 1995 Passenger - David Fisher, September 6, 2019 Passenger Linda Fisher, September 27, 2021 Passenger Jacob Fisher, September 24, 2017 Passenger Nacy Fisher, July 1, 1997 Vehicle 3 2013 Ford F150 Operator Gary William Robertson, March 24, 1969 Vehicle 3 2006 Chevrolet Equinox Operator Lauren Lee Houde, October 20, 1992 Passenger Jessica Taylor Miller, July 20, 1999 Passenger Jose Asmin Amaya, December 1, 2007 Passenger Monique Lynn Collins, February 9, 1996 During the investigation, it was revealed that the vehicles 2 4 were stopped for a prior crash clean up in the southbound travel lane of Maryland Route 97 prior to Maryland Route 496. Vehicle 1 was traveling south on Maryland Route 97 when it failed to control speed to avoid a crash and struck vehicle 2. The Kia was traveling 41MPH. Vehicle 1 then struck vehicle 3. Vehicle 3 then struck vehicle 4. The occupants of vehicle 2 sustained life-threatening injuries. Onkst displayed signs of alcohol impairment and a blood test was completed.Blood test results still pending. Onkst had a valid learner permit. Black license was suspended. Onkst did not have a supervising driver. The full reconstruction is attached as a PDF. Violations of Maryland Transportation Article The primary cause of this collision was determined to be the failure of Maura Ashlynn Onkst to obey: TA 21-801B Failure to control vehicle speed on highway to avoid collision Contributory factors of this collision was determined to be the failure of Maura Ashlynn Onkst to obey: TA 16-101A1 Driving motor vehicle on highway without required license authorization TA 10 105B1 holder of learners permit driving without required supervision Case Status Upon approval this case will be presented to the Office of the States Attorney in the County of Carroll. A supplement will be completed for an addition investigation or charges. Investigator Corporal J Lantz 5563 Collision Reconstruction Specialist / sUAS Pilot State of Maryland Department of State Police CRASH Team / sUAS Team Golden Ring Office 8908 Kelso Drive Essex, Maryland 21221 James.Lantz@Maryland.Gov

Crash Investigation Supplement Section I. Narrative On 5/19/2023 at approximately 0021 hours, I was working an overtime assignment when I was requested to respond to Littlestown Pike (RT 97) at Bachmans Valley Road (RT 496) for an accident reconstruction. Upon arrival, I observed three vehicles and a horse and buggy that were involved in a collision on the southbound side of the roadway. The preliminary investigation revealed that two vehicles and the horse and buggy were stopped due to a previous collision south of their location, when a Kia Forte failed to stop, striking the rear of the horse and buggy. It was also determined that the driver of the KIA Forte was possibly under the influence of alcohol at the time of the collision. Due to this information and the serious injuries suffered by occupants of the horse and buggy, I contacted Corporal Lantz of the Maryland State Police CRASH Team, and he responded to the scene. I assisted CPL Lantz by marking and photographing the scene. This concluded my involvement in this incident. Section II. I then reviewed my Field Arrest Report, BWC Footage with timestamp, and the CAD notes for the investigation. All three of these documents are accurate records of the events as recorded. All three documents revealed that the accurate time of arrest was in fact 0104 hours on 5/19/2023 and not 2039 hours. All events occurred in Carroll County, MD.
